endpoints.name: Account
endpoints.Synopsis:
Account represents the accounts that you keep to track your business. Account is a component of a chart of accounts, and is part of a ledger. You can use Account to record the total monetary amount that is allocated for a specific use. Accounts are one of five basic types:

  • Asset
  • Liability
  • Revenue (Income)
  • Expenses
  • Equity

Business Rules


The Account object has the following business rules and validations:

  • The account name must be unique.
  • The Account Name is required.
  • The Account SubType is required.

methods.Synopsis: This operation creates a new entity of the type Account
This operation retrieve an entity of type Account searched using ID
This operation retrieve all entities of type Account
This operation Updates entity of the type Account
This operation deletes the account for the given account Id

endpoints.name: Bill
endpoints.Synopsis:
The Bill represents an expense to the business. An expense is of the following types:

  • Item-based expense for the item that the business owner purchases for resale.
  • Account-based expense for the amount that the business owner spends on an account, such as expense incurred on the Advertisement Expense account.

Business Rules


The Bill object has the following business rules and validations:

  • A bill must have reference to a vendor in the header.
  • A bill must have at least one line that describes the item or account.
  • An Account-based expense is a line with the AccountId, Amount, and Description attributes.
  • An Item-based expense is a line with the AccountId, Amount, Description, Qty, UnitPrice, ItemId, and ClassId attributes.

Available only to QuickBooks Online Plus subscribers.

methods.Synopsis: This operation creates a new entity of the type Bill
This operation retrieve an entity of type Bill searched using ID
This operation retrieve all entities of type Bill
This operation Updates entity of the type Bill
This operation deletes the bill for the given bill Id

endpoints.name: BillPayment
endpoints.Synopsis:
BillPayment represents the financial transaction of payment of bills that the business owner receives from a vendor for goods or services purchased from the vendor. QBO supports bill payments through a credit card or a bank account.


Business Rules


The BillPayment object has the following business rules and validations:

  • A bill payment must have reference to a vendor by EntityId in the header.
  • A bill payment must specify a credit card account or a bank account.

This operation retrieve an entity of type BillPayment searched using ID

This operation deletes the BillPayment for the given BillPayment Id

endpoints.name: CashPurchase
endpoints.Synopsis:
CashPurchase represents an expense to the business as a cash transaction. An expense is of the following types:

  • Item-based expense for the item that the business owner purchases for resale.
  • Account-based expense for the amount that the business owner spends on an account, such as expense incurred on the Advertisement Expense account.

This is a QBO-only transaction.


Business Rules


The CashPurchase object has the following business rules and validations:

  • An Account-based expense is a line with the AccountId, Amount, and Description attributes.
  • An Item-based expense is a line with the AccountId, Amount, Description, Qty, UnitPrice, and ItemId attributes.

endpoints.name: Check
endpoints.Synopsis:
Financial transaction representing a payment to a payee. The Check represents an expense to the business paid as a check transaction. The expense is of the following types:

  • Item based expense for the item that is purchased for reselling.
  • Account based expense for the amount spend on an account, such as expense incurred on "advertisement expense" account.

Business Rules


The Check object has the following business rules and validations:

  • An Account-based expense is a line with the AccountId, Amount, and Description attributes.
  • An Item-based expense is a line with the AccountId, Amount, Description, Qty, UnitPrice, ItemId, CustomerId, BillableStatus, and ClassId attributes.

endpoints.name: Class
endpoints.Synopsis:
Classes provide a way to track different segments of the business, and to break down the income and expenses for each segment. Classes provide a system for categorizing transactions that goes beyond the basic ways of assigning transactions to expense or income accounts. With classes, it is possible to categorize each detail line on a transaction. This allows the customer to write one check to the office supply store for things bought for two different business units and still track the business unit for those purchases.

Example uses of classes:

  • Department
  • Enterprise
  • Properties
  • Work categories (plumbing, electrical, etc.)
  • Manufacturers
  • Partners
  • Product Lines

endpoints.name: CreditCardCharge
endpoints.Synopsis:
Financial transaction representing a charge for purchase of goods or services. The CreditCardCharge represents an expense to the business as a credit card charge transaction. The expense is of the following types:

  • Item based expense for the item that is purchased for reselling.
  • Account based expense for the amount spend on an account, such as expense incurred on "advertisement expense" account.

Business Rules


The CreditCardCharge object has the following business rules and validations:

  • An Account-based expense is a line with the AccountId, Amount, and Description attributes.
  • An Item-based expense is a line with the AccountId, Amount, Description, Qty, UnitPrice, and ItemId attributes.
  • CreditCardCharge must have the total expense equal to the total expense of line items.

endpoints.Synopsis: The Customer represents the consumer of the service or the product that your business offers. QBO allows categorizing the customers in a way that is meaningful to the business. For example, you can set up a category of customers to indicate which industry a customer represents, the geographic location of a customer, or how a customer came to know about the business. The categorization can be then used for reports or mails.

endpoints.name: Entitlements
endpoints.Synopsis:
The entitlements API retrieves the features available to a company, identified by the company's realm ID (shown as the Company ID in QuickBooks Online). The features available are determined by the type of company established during QuickBooks Online setup. These features are a super set of those enabled for the company by preferences and those enabled for a user by permissions.

Once you have determined that a feature is available, you have to call the preferences API to determine if the feature is enabled.

methods.Synopsis: This operation retrieve an entity of type Entitlements searched using ID

endpoints.name: Estimate
endpoints.Synopsis:
The Estimate represents a proposal for a financial transaction from a business to a customer for goods or services proposed to be sold, including proposed pricing. It is also known as quote. Note: Available only to the QuickBooks Online Plus subscribers.


Business Rules


The Estimate object has the following business rules and validations:

  • An estimate must have at least one line that describes an item.
  • An estimate must have a reference to a customer in the header.

endpoints.name: Invoice
endpoints.Synopsis:
The Invoice object represents an invoice to a customer. Invoice could be based on salesterm with invoice and due dates for payment. Invoice supports sales tax, and shipping charges as a special line item. Invoice can be printed and emailed to a customer.


Business Rules


The Invoice object has the following business rules and validations:

  • An invoice must have at least one line that describes the item and an amount.
  • An invoice must have a reference to a customer in the header.

endpoints.name: Job
endpoints.Synopsis:
A Job is a way to track larger orders such as those placed by different departments of the same organization. You can use it for many purposes such as tracking projects that belong to the same customers. It can also represent a person if you are tracking members for a team or a league. In QuickBooks Online, a Job is called a sub-customer, and you will find documentation referencing sub-customers instead of Job.


Business Rules


The Job object has the following business rules and validations:li>To create a Job object, you must have the parent customer in place already.

  • You may have as many jobs as you want per customer, but you can only create Jobs for 4 levels deep.
  • A job has all the same attributes as a customer except that it will always belong to a customer and optionally may belong to a larger job.

endpoints.name: SalesReceipt
endpoints.Synopsis:
SalesReceipt represents the sales receipt that is given to a customer. A sales receipt is similar to an invoice. However, for a sales receipt, payment is received as part of the sale of goods and services. The sales receipt specifies a deposit account where the customer deposits the payment. If the deposit account is not specified, the payment type is classified as Undeposited Account.


Business Rules


The SalesReceipt object has the following business rules and validations:

  • A sales receipt must have at least one line that describes the item and an amount.

endpoints.name: SalesTerm
endpoints.Synopsis:
The SalesTerm object represents the terms under which a sale is made, typically expressed in the form of days due after the goods are received. There is an optional discount part of the sales term, where a discount of total amount can automatically be applied if payment is made within the stipulated time.

For example, net 30 indicates that you must make the payment within 30 days; 2%/15 net 60 indicates that you must make the payment within 60 days, and you can get a discount of 2% if you make payment within 15 days. SalesTerm also supports the ability to specify the absolute due date, a number of days from a start date, a percent discount, or an absolute discount.

The SalesTerm name itself is a text-only attribute and the desired application of the sales term must be coded. For example, a common term such as Net30Days is explicitly coded as a calculated DueDateTime or as a PaymentTermsDateTime and NumberOfDays.
